1
00:00:08,967 --> 00:00:13,096
"THE WORLD'S DOORS OPEN FIRST
TO THOSE WHO ASK" - SOCRATES

2
00:00:13,180 --> 00:00:14,348
<i>Hocrates,</i>

3
00:00:14,598 --> 00:00:17,059
<i>the last disciple of Socrates.</i>

4
00:00:17,976 --> 00:00:21,939
<i>He was loved by his mentor</i>
<i>for his endless curiosity and questions.</i>

5
00:00:22,523 --> 00:00:23,732
<i>But after Socrates' passing,</i>

6
00:00:24,024 --> 00:00:25,859
<i>he was banished by his peers</i>

7
00:00:26,610 --> 00:00:28,612
<i>for asking too many questions.</i>

8
00:00:29,530 --> 00:00:32,741
<i>Since then, he has lived millennia</i>
<i>away from his homeland</i>

9
00:00:32,824 --> 00:00:33,867
<i>as a philosopher,</i>

10
00:00:34,076 --> 00:00:35,327
<i>an ordinary citizen,</i>

11
00:00:35,410 --> 00:00:36,578
<i>an athlete,</i>

12
00:00:37,329 --> 00:00:38,413
<i>an advisor,</i>

13
00:00:38,497 --> 00:00:39,873
<i>and a show host.</i>

14
00:00:40,374 --> 00:00:44,127
<i>He continues to explore humanity</i>
<i>and the meaning of life</i>

15
00:00:44,211 --> 00:00:45,420
<i>as an immortal.</i>

16
00:00:45,879 --> 00:00:46,880
<i>And...</i>

17
00:00:47,422 --> 00:00:48,966
<i>in 2026,</i>

18
00:00:49,550 --> 00:00:51,677
<i>he opened a bookshop</i>

19
00:00:51,760 --> 00:00:54,513
<i>in the cutest neighborhood in the world,</i>
<i>Kangho-dong.</i>

20
00:00:58,850 --> 00:01:00,394
I'm here to sell a book.

21
00:01:02,145 --> 00:01:05,232
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

22
00:01:07,734 --> 00:01:10,696
When is the customer coming?
They made a reservation.

23
00:01:13,031 --> 00:01:14,992
This takes me back.

24
00:01:15,075 --> 00:01:16,368
A long time has passed since then.

25
00:01:21,623 --> 00:01:27,629
FIRST BOOK: <i>LETTERS TO A YOUNG POET</i>

26
00:01:37,681 --> 00:01:38,765
Excuse me.

27
00:01:41,226 --> 00:01:43,729
HA JUNG-WOO
ACTOR

28
00:01:43,812 --> 00:01:45,397
I'm here to sell a book.

29
00:01:47,566 --> 00:01:48,775
- It's you, right?
- Yes.

30
00:01:48,859 --> 00:01:50,110
- The one who made the reservation.
- Yes.

31
00:01:50,193 --> 00:01:52,195
- All right, right this way.
- Okay.

32
00:01:52,279 --> 00:01:54,031
- Make yourself at home.
- Thanks.

33
00:01:54,615 --> 00:01:57,284
This is a space
where people are read like books,

34
00:01:57,367 --> 00:01:59,036
- called Hodong's Bookshop,
- I see.

35
00:01:59,119 --> 00:02:01,538
which is located in
the cutest neighborhood in the world,

36
00:02:01,705 --> 00:02:03,915
- Kangho-dong.
- It's great to be here.

37
00:02:03,999 --> 00:02:05,542
- Welcome.
- Thank you.

38
00:02:06,918 --> 00:02:09,087
- You're here to sell a book, right?
- I am.

39
00:02:09,171 --> 00:02:11,340
In this bookshop,
we don't accept cash or credit cards

40
00:02:11,423 --> 00:02:14,509
- when buying and selling books.
- I see.

41
00:02:14,635 --> 00:02:16,678
- Here, we only accept stories.
- I see.

42
00:02:16,762 --> 00:02:18,430
- Since you're here to sell a book,
- Yes.

43
00:02:18,513 --> 00:02:20,390
- why don't we hear your story first
- All right.

44
00:02:20,515 --> 00:02:22,934
and set a price for the book?

45
00:02:23,018 --> 00:02:24,394
- That sounds nice.
- Right?

46
00:02:24,478 --> 00:02:25,854
- Yes.
- Okay.

47
00:02:26,980 --> 00:02:28,190
What's so funny?

48
00:02:28,273 --> 00:02:29,566
I'm just glad to see you.

49
00:02:29,650 --> 00:02:31,026
- Sorry?
- I'm glad to see you.

50
00:02:31,109 --> 00:02:32,986
- Do you know me?
- No, it's just...

51
00:02:34,404 --> 00:02:35,864
It's just good to see you.

52
00:02:37,074 --> 00:02:38,200
Do I look funny to you?

53
00:02:38,283 --> 00:02:39,409
No, not at all.

54
00:02:39,951 --> 00:02:41,828
- No, right?
- This is great.

55
00:02:42,162 --> 00:02:43,288
Which part is great?

56
00:02:43,372 --> 00:02:46,917
You've been alive for 2,000 years,

57
00:02:47,292 --> 00:02:49,961
- and here I am talking to you.
- Right.

58
00:02:50,295 --> 00:02:52,047
If you could follow me,

59
00:02:52,130 --> 00:02:54,174
- I can show you.
- Okay.

60
00:02:54,257 --> 00:02:57,302
- This is my mentor, Socrates.
- I see.

61
00:02:57,386 --> 00:02:58,845
- This is a good quote from him.
- Right.

62
00:02:58,929 --> 00:03:01,890
"The world's doors open first
to those who ask."

63
00:03:01,973 --> 00:03:02,974
- That's true.
- Yes.

64
00:03:03,058 --> 00:03:05,102
But I was cast out for asking too many.

65
00:03:05,185 --> 00:03:07,396
- Oh, that's a shame.
- Yes.

66
00:03:07,479 --> 00:03:09,481
- They said I asked way too many questions
- I see.

67
00:03:09,564 --> 00:03:11,149
- and kicked me out.
- I see.

68
00:03:11,733 --> 00:03:15,153
- In this one, I'm next to Einstein.
- Right.

69
00:03:15,612 --> 00:03:17,155
- This was at NASA.
- Yes.

70
00:03:17,239 --> 00:03:18,782
- Apollo.
- Apollo 13.

71
00:03:18,865 --> 00:03:21,034
I was really nervous during the countdown.

72
00:03:22,786 --> 00:03:24,329
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

73
00:03:24,413 --> 00:03:25,914
All right, I asked you

74
00:03:25,997 --> 00:03:28,208
to write down your personal information.

75
00:03:28,542 --> 00:03:30,544
HE FILLED IN THE RESERVATION CARD
And you did.

76
00:03:30,627 --> 00:03:31,545
Yes, I did.

77
00:03:31,628 --> 00:03:33,755
- Let's go over it together.
- Okay.

78
00:03:34,131 --> 00:03:35,382
What's your name?

79
00:03:35,465 --> 00:03:37,050
My name is Ha Jung-woo.

80
00:03:37,134 --> 00:03:38,844
- Ha Jung-woo... Right.
- Yes.

81
00:03:39,052 --> 00:03:40,178
Is it your real name?

82
00:03:40,262 --> 00:03:41,805
My real name is Kim Sung-hoon.

83
00:03:41,888 --> 00:03:43,265
- Is it really?
- Yes.

84
00:03:43,348 --> 00:03:45,434
- Is Ha Jung-woo a stage name?
- Yes.

85
00:03:45,517 --> 00:03:47,060
Kim Sung-hoon is a nice name.

86
00:03:47,144 --> 00:03:49,312
It is, but I decided not to go by it.

87
00:03:49,396 --> 00:03:51,189
Did a naming center or someone else
give it to you?

88
00:03:51,940 --> 00:03:54,693
My agency came to me with a few names.

89
00:03:54,776 --> 00:03:56,570
Among all of those names,

90
00:03:56,653 --> 00:04:00,115
my father picked this one.

91
00:04:00,198 --> 00:04:01,491
- Out of all those names?
- Yes.

92
00:04:01,575 --> 00:04:02,951
What were the other candidates?

93
00:04:03,034 --> 00:04:05,704
- There was "Geum Sung-hoon."
- Geum...

94
00:04:05,787 --> 00:04:07,581
The name is reminiscent of
actors in Hong Kong films.

95
00:04:07,831 --> 00:04:09,958
- Back then... That's right.
- Geum Sung-hoon?

96
00:04:10,041 --> 00:04:11,710
- Like Geum Sung-mu, or Takeshi Kaneshiro.
- Yes.

97
00:04:11,793 --> 00:04:13,795
Hong Kong films were popular back then,

98
00:04:13,879 --> 00:04:15,172
so they suggested that name.

99
00:04:15,255 --> 00:04:17,132
- Hong Kong noir was huge at the time.
- Exactly.

100
00:04:17,215 --> 00:04:18,425
I'm glad we didn't go with
the other names.

101
00:04:18,717 --> 00:04:20,844
I can see in this reservation card

102
00:04:20,927 --> 00:04:22,387
- Yes?
- that there are various things you do.

103
00:04:22,471 --> 00:04:24,556
- Right.
- Could you tell me?

104
00:04:25,557 --> 00:04:27,768
I'm also a director,

105
00:04:27,851 --> 00:04:30,437
a painter, a writer, and so on.

106
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:32,773
Which one do you put as your occupation
on your arrival card?

107
00:04:33,648 --> 00:04:34,733
Businessman.

108
00:04:37,027 --> 00:04:38,737
- You put "businessman"?
- Yes.

109
00:04:38,820 --> 00:04:40,781
- When I'm going through immigration,
- Yes?

110
00:04:40,864 --> 00:04:42,115
if I say I'm an actor,

111
00:04:42,199 --> 00:04:44,868
they keep asking questions
since it's not a common job.

112
00:04:45,035 --> 00:04:47,329
Then, there's no end to it.

113
00:04:47,412 --> 00:04:48,914
I have to keep explaining.

114
00:04:48,997 --> 00:04:51,458
And if I say I'm a director,
it would be worse.

115
00:04:51,541 --> 00:04:53,543
So I just say I'm in the film business.

116
00:04:54,211 --> 00:04:57,005
One time, I put "painter"
when I was going to Japan.

117
00:04:57,088 --> 00:04:59,174
- Did they have a problem with it?
- Yes.

118
00:04:59,257 --> 00:05:00,342
In Niigata.

119
00:05:00,592 --> 00:05:03,136
They said, "Why would a painter
come to Niigata?"

120
00:05:03,553 --> 00:05:06,556
They kept asking me,
even though my English was limited.

121
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:07,974
I had a difficult time.

122
00:05:08,099 --> 00:05:11,394
I thought people in Japan
would recognize you by now?

123
00:05:11,478 --> 00:05:13,188
That happened about 20 years ago.

124
00:05:13,271 --> 00:05:16,024
It was around the time
I held my first solo exhibition.

125
00:05:16,107 --> 00:05:17,776
So, as a painter, I was...

126
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:19,444
cocky, you know?

127
00:05:19,528 --> 00:05:22,364
I was full of myself at the time.

128
00:05:22,447 --> 00:05:23,490
But I learned a lesson
with that experience.

129
00:05:23,573 --> 00:05:25,867
Now, I never mention that I'm a painter.

130
00:05:26,493 --> 00:05:28,578
- I get it. You were just starting out.
- Right.

131
00:05:28,703 --> 00:05:31,873
It also had to do with my appearance
and attitude at the time.

132
00:05:32,123 --> 00:05:35,669
I had facial hair,
and I didn't look exactly clean.

133
00:05:35,752 --> 00:05:37,921
- You were a free spirit
- That's right.

134
00:05:38,004 --> 00:05:39,881
HOW HE LOOKED THEN
as an artist.

135
00:05:39,965 --> 00:05:43,093
I can see how an immigration officer
would find that unusual.

136
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:46,596
When I was younger,
I thought it was stylish.

137
00:05:46,680 --> 00:05:49,391
I even used to wear
a vintage military jacket.

138
00:05:49,641 --> 00:05:52,477
Now, I never wear
something like that when I'm flying.

139
00:05:52,644 --> 00:05:55,689
One time, I had that on
when I got to the Atlanta airport,

140
00:05:55,772 --> 00:05:58,692
and they took me to the back office
at immigration.

141
00:05:59,192 --> 00:06:01,152
- I told them I was an actor.
- Right.

142
00:06:01,236 --> 00:06:03,196
- You said you were an actor?
- Yes.

143
00:06:03,280 --> 00:06:05,532
They kept me there for two hours.

144
00:06:06,491 --> 00:06:09,035
The Internet wasn't as advanced back then.

145
00:06:09,119 --> 00:06:11,204
You got mistaken for a terrorist.

146
00:06:11,288 --> 00:06:13,164
That's right. It got complicated.

147
00:06:13,248 --> 00:06:15,417
They wanted a name
so I said, "Ha Jung-woo."

148
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:16,501
"Ha Jung-woo..."

149
00:06:16,585 --> 00:06:18,211
But the name on my passport
was Kim Sung-hoon.

150
00:06:18,295 --> 00:06:20,922
So they were like, "What's this?"
It got complicated.

151
00:06:21,006 --> 00:06:23,425
I was in this sort of holding cell

152
00:06:23,508 --> 00:06:25,635
- for over two hours.
- Holding cell? Really?

153
00:06:25,719 --> 00:06:28,054
Yes, at the Atlanta airport.

154
00:06:28,138 --> 00:06:31,182
Every second I spent there was terrifying.

155
00:06:31,266 --> 00:06:32,642
I thought to myself,

156
00:06:32,726 --> 00:06:35,103
"One false move
and I'll be sent back to South Korea."

157
00:06:35,186 --> 00:06:37,981
I guess to them, it didn't seem like

158
00:06:38,064 --> 00:06:39,983
you had the look of an actor.

159
00:06:40,108 --> 00:06:41,192
- I guess.
- Right?

160
00:06:41,276 --> 00:06:43,528
I confidently put "actor,"
and they were like,

161
00:06:44,446 --> 00:06:45,447
"Who are you?"

162
00:06:48,158 --> 00:06:48,992
So that happened.

163
00:06:49,534 --> 00:06:50,785
- Anyway, you're here
- Yes?

164
00:06:50,869 --> 00:06:52,412
- to sell a book.
- Yes.

165
00:06:52,495 --> 00:06:53,955
What's the title of the book?

166
00:06:54,789 --> 00:06:57,000
<i>Letters to a Young Poet.</i>

167
00:06:57,083 --> 00:06:59,044
I see!

168
00:06:59,169 --> 00:07:00,337
Rainer...

169
00:07:00,545 --> 00:07:02,756
- Yes. Rainer Maria Rilke.
- Maria... Rilke.

170
00:07:02,839 --> 00:07:05,425
- The famous poet, right?
- That's right.

171
00:07:09,012 --> 00:07:10,430
I've met Rilke in person.

172
00:07:10,513 --> 00:07:11,473
Oh, have you?

173
00:07:11,556 --> 00:07:13,016
- We were close, actually.
- I see.

174
00:07:14,351 --> 00:07:16,478
From what I can remember,

175
00:07:16,561 --> 00:07:18,813
Rilke really liked to write people back.

176
00:07:18,897 --> 00:07:21,024
- Yes, even though he was always late.
- Yes.

177
00:07:23,944 --> 00:07:26,321
MY PAL RILKE, ME, MR. RODIN
PHOTO PROVIDED BY HOCRATES HIMSELF

178
00:07:26,571 --> 00:07:27,739
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

179
00:07:28,239 --> 00:07:29,240
HA JUNG-WOO'S FAVORITE BOOK

180
00:07:29,324 --> 00:07:30,784
<i>LETTERS TO A YOUNG POET</i>
BY RAINER MARIA RILKE

181
00:07:30,867 --> 00:07:32,369
A COLLECTION OF RILKE'S LETTERS
TO A YOUNG POET

182
00:07:32,452 --> 00:07:34,245
IT TALKS ABOUT
HOW ONE CAN ENDURE LONELINESS AND ANXIETY

183
00:07:34,579 --> 00:07:36,331
INTRODUCE YOUR FAVORITE BOOK
So this

184
00:07:36,414 --> 00:07:37,958
- is your favorite book?
- Yes.

185
00:07:38,041 --> 00:07:40,126
An aspiring poet named Kappus

186
00:07:40,210 --> 00:07:43,421
writes in his letters
to the famous poet Rainer Maria Rilke

187
00:07:43,505 --> 00:07:46,299
that he wants to be a poet

188
00:07:46,383 --> 00:07:49,010
and asks for advice on what he should do.

189
00:07:49,094 --> 00:07:51,763
- Right.
- Rilke writes back to him.

190
00:07:51,846 --> 00:07:55,183
This book is
a collection of those letters.

191
00:07:55,308 --> 00:07:57,519
In today's terms,

192
00:07:57,602 --> 00:07:59,688
- it's as if an aspiring actor
- Yes.

193
00:07:59,771 --> 00:08:01,731
who wanted to know
whether they were good at acting

194
00:08:01,815 --> 00:08:03,525
- filmed themselves acting
- Right.

195
00:08:03,608 --> 00:08:05,276
and sent it to a superstar actor

196
00:08:05,360 --> 00:08:06,945
- like you, via email.
- Yes.

197
00:08:07,028 --> 00:08:08,905
- Asking "Please tell me what you think
- It's similar to that.

198
00:08:08,989 --> 00:08:10,198
- about my acting."
- Yes.

199
00:08:10,281 --> 00:08:12,242
- That's what it's like, right?
- Right.

200
00:08:12,325 --> 00:08:13,493
You've experienced
something like this before, haven't you?

201
00:08:13,576 --> 00:08:14,744
Yes, I have.

202
00:08:14,869 --> 00:08:18,248
Ever since I made an Instagram account,

203
00:08:18,581 --> 00:08:21,918
a lot of people have been DMing me.

204
00:08:22,002 --> 00:08:23,753
- Young aspiring actors?
- Yes.

205
00:08:23,837 --> 00:08:25,338
Did you write back to them?

206
00:08:25,422 --> 00:08:27,424
Yes, some of them.

207
00:08:27,549 --> 00:08:29,217
When I read their messages,

208
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:32,637
I can tell
if they're really serious or not

209
00:08:32,721 --> 00:08:35,056
- from the weight of the message.
- Right.

210
00:08:35,265 --> 00:08:38,268
Some of them
just write to me out of curiosity

211
00:08:38,351 --> 00:08:40,520
because I'm an actor and a celebrity,

212
00:08:40,603 --> 00:08:43,481
but some send genuine messages
that have substance.

213
00:08:43,648 --> 00:08:46,067
In those cases, I write back.

214
00:08:46,860 --> 00:08:48,319
- Even before your debut,
- Yes?

215
00:08:48,403 --> 00:08:49,571
you taught acting.

216
00:08:49,654 --> 00:08:52,323
Yes, I was
a part-time acting tutor in college.

217
00:08:52,407 --> 00:08:53,992
- Before you went pro?
- Yes.

218
00:08:54,075 --> 00:08:55,660
I did it for a long time.

219
00:08:55,744 --> 00:08:57,787
In my sophomore year,

220
00:08:57,871 --> 00:09:01,541
I taught at an acting academy
that an actor friend of mine founded

221
00:09:01,624 --> 00:09:03,334
as an instructor.

222
00:09:03,626 --> 00:09:05,295
After my military service,

223
00:09:05,378 --> 00:09:07,589
I started to give private lessons.

224
00:09:07,672 --> 00:09:09,215
Did any of your students
become professional actors?

225
00:09:09,299 --> 00:09:12,052
Yes, there's Koo Kyo-hwan for example.

226
00:09:12,552 --> 00:09:13,928
And there is...

227
00:09:14,012 --> 00:09:15,138
He's a big actor!

228
00:09:15,221 --> 00:09:16,306
- He is.
- Right?

229
00:09:16,389 --> 00:09:18,349
I taught him for two years, since he
retook the college entrance exams.

230
00:09:18,433 --> 00:09:20,602
- He's a charismatic actor.
- Yes.

231
00:09:20,685 --> 00:09:22,312
Even back then,

232
00:09:22,395 --> 00:09:24,981
- he was very unique.
- Right.

233
00:09:25,065 --> 00:09:27,275
There's something
in his eyes, isn't there?

234
00:09:27,358 --> 00:09:29,694
He has this energy. He's captivating.

235
00:09:29,778 --> 00:09:32,989
There are also students
who have been in some films.

236
00:09:33,073 --> 00:09:34,449
Baek Sung-chul, for instance.

237
00:09:34,532 --> 00:09:36,076
- I see.
- Yes.

238
00:09:36,159 --> 00:09:37,744
- Right.
- If you look at them,

239
00:09:37,827 --> 00:09:40,288
Kyo-hwan got into college
on his second attempt,

240
00:09:40,371 --> 00:09:43,583
and Sung-chul on his third.

241
00:09:43,750 --> 00:09:44,918
At the end of the day,

242
00:09:45,001 --> 00:09:48,088
it's not important how many times
someone retook the college entrance exams.

243
00:09:49,589 --> 00:09:54,427
Looking back on
more than 20 years that have passed

244
00:09:54,511 --> 00:09:57,388
and seeing the young actors
who are successful right now,

245
00:09:57,722 --> 00:09:59,140
I think people don't have to be so anxious

246
00:09:59,224 --> 00:10:01,601
about re-trying two, three, or four times
to get to the school they want.

247
00:10:01,684 --> 00:10:03,728
It doesn't matter
how many tries you made to get in.

248
00:10:03,812 --> 00:10:04,687
Don't you think so?

249
00:10:04,813 --> 00:10:07,065
Isn't that what this book is also about?

250
00:10:07,148 --> 00:10:08,149
That's right.

251
00:10:08,233 --> 00:10:09,859
So, you can say

252
00:10:10,026 --> 00:10:11,903
that it doesn't just apply to poets

253
00:10:11,986 --> 00:10:14,030
- or artists, for that matter.
- Right.

254
00:10:14,114 --> 00:10:16,157
Throughout life,

255
00:10:16,241 --> 00:10:18,201
we all go through dilemmas

256
00:10:18,284 --> 00:10:20,411
and sometimes even get lost.

257
00:10:20,495 --> 00:10:21,704
In those times,

258
00:10:21,788 --> 00:10:24,165
I think this book can serve as a guide

259
00:10:24,249 --> 00:10:27,252
that provides some answers.

260
00:10:28,837 --> 00:10:30,296
<i>Letters to a Young Poet.</i>

261
00:10:30,380 --> 00:10:32,841
- Now, we have to set a price
- Okay.

262
00:10:32,924 --> 00:10:34,259
- for this book.
- Okay.

263
00:10:34,342 --> 00:10:36,761
- So let's really get down to talking.
- All right.

264
00:10:36,845 --> 00:10:39,681
REGARDING HA JUNG-WOO'S DREAM
Your first life keyword is "Dream."

265
00:10:40,223 --> 00:10:44,185
Rilke asks the aspiring poet Kappus,

266
00:10:44,519 --> 00:10:48,231
"Would you rather die than not write?"

267
00:10:49,440 --> 00:10:51,192
Rilke tells him to ask himself.

268
00:10:51,609 --> 00:10:53,153
"Are you really committed?"

269
00:10:53,361 --> 00:10:55,655
- That's what he's trying to say, right?
- Right.

270
00:10:56,573 --> 00:10:58,116
Being committed.

271
00:10:58,241 --> 00:11:00,702
- Was your dream always to be an actor?
- Yes.

272
00:11:00,785 --> 00:11:04,038
To the point that you'd choose death
over not being an actor?

273
00:11:04,122 --> 00:11:06,166
When you're young,
you have many dreams, right?

274
00:11:06,249 --> 00:11:08,042
Strangely, I only had one dream.

275
00:11:08,793 --> 00:11:10,003
I wanted to be an actor.

276
00:11:12,005 --> 00:11:14,883
But that dream didn't
just hit me in the head

277
00:11:14,966 --> 00:11:18,094
- out of nowhere one day.
- I see.

278
00:11:18,178 --> 00:11:19,888
It came to me naturally.

279
00:11:19,971 --> 00:11:21,848
Throughout my life,

280
00:11:21,931 --> 00:11:25,059
I've thought about having different jobs,

281
00:11:25,143 --> 00:11:27,562
but they weren't dreams.

282
00:11:27,770 --> 00:11:31,316
What's the legendary story that
you figured out how to act at age three?

283
00:11:31,858 --> 00:11:33,026
Oh, that.

284
00:11:34,068 --> 00:11:37,322
I was crying
because my parents scolded me.

285
00:11:37,447 --> 00:11:40,325
But at one point,
I detached myself from the situation.

286
00:11:40,408 --> 00:11:42,535
It was like having a lucid dream.

287
00:11:43,036 --> 00:11:45,622
So I thought,
"What's this? Let me stop crying."

288
00:11:45,705 --> 00:11:47,123
And I did.

289
00:11:47,832 --> 00:11:49,167
Then, "Let me cry again."

290
00:11:49,250 --> 00:11:51,211
And I started crying again.

291
00:11:51,544 --> 00:11:54,464
It was a strange experience
to have as a kid.

292
00:11:54,547 --> 00:11:58,259
I thought, "This is how actors act."

293
00:11:58,801 --> 00:12:01,638
I realized that at a young age.

294
00:12:01,804 --> 00:12:02,847
Isn't that strange?

295
00:12:02,931 --> 00:12:04,599
- I remember crying as a kid, too.
- Right.

296
00:12:04,682 --> 00:12:06,267
- I had a similar experience.
- Okay.

297
00:12:06,351 --> 00:12:08,394
What's weird was that I was crying,

298
00:12:08,728 --> 00:12:09,854
pretty hard, actually,

299
00:12:09,938 --> 00:12:12,148
and then I forgot what I was crying about.

300
00:12:12,232 --> 00:12:13,942
There must've been a reason
I was crying that hard.

301
00:12:14,108 --> 00:12:16,027
- Right.
- So I felt awkward.

302
00:12:16,110 --> 00:12:17,904
- I remember that.
- I see.

303
00:12:18,029 --> 00:12:19,572
I was probably crying
because I was hungry.

304
00:12:20,365 --> 00:12:23,409
That could totally have been the case.

305
00:12:24,786 --> 00:12:26,704
You've been around for 2,000 years.

306
00:12:26,871 --> 00:12:29,332
You've probably experienced hunger
more than most.

307
00:12:29,415 --> 00:12:30,416
- Right?
- Yes.

308
00:12:30,625 --> 00:12:32,919
ACTOR KIM YONG-GEON
Did your dad have influence?

309
00:12:33,002 --> 00:12:35,421
- Yes, he definitely had a big influence.
- I see.

310
00:12:35,505 --> 00:12:36,589
When you're young,

311
00:12:36,673 --> 00:12:39,676
everything your dad does seems cool

312
00:12:39,759 --> 00:12:41,261
- and great.
- And important.

313
00:12:41,344 --> 00:12:42,845
Yes. You want to do what he does.

314
00:12:42,929 --> 00:12:45,139
I spent a lot of time
with my dad as a kid.

315
00:12:45,223 --> 00:12:46,599
We went on trips together.

316
00:12:46,724 --> 00:12:49,185
And I grew up watching
shows that my dad was in.

317
00:12:49,269 --> 00:12:52,730
<i>Country Diaries</i> would air
on Tuesdays back then,

318
00:12:52,814 --> 00:12:55,400
and on weekends,
<i>The Moon of Seoul</i> and<i> Rose of Betrayal.</i>

319
00:12:55,483 --> 00:12:58,152
Every day of the week,
there was a show on TV.

320
00:12:58,236 --> 00:13:00,154
When he was in a weekday soap opera,

321
00:13:00,238 --> 00:13:04,367
I would watch it air at 7 p.m.,

322
00:13:04,534 --> 00:13:07,453
and I would think,
"I want to be like my dad."

323
00:13:07,537 --> 00:13:09,580
That idea formed in my head over time.

324
00:13:09,664 --> 00:13:12,250
<i>Country Diaries</i>,
which your father starred in,

325
00:13:12,333 --> 00:13:14,669
was one of the pieces that influenced you.

326
00:13:14,752 --> 00:13:18,298
But I heard that there's a film
that had a big impact on you.

327
00:13:18,381 --> 00:13:19,549
- Right
- Leaving...

328
00:13:19,632 --> 00:13:23,136
It's the film <i>Leaving Las Vegas</i>.

329
00:13:23,219 --> 00:13:26,055
I first watched it
when I was in high school.

330
00:13:26,139 --> 00:13:27,849
Through that film,

331
00:13:27,932 --> 00:13:31,185
Nicholas Cage earned
the Academy Award for Best Actor.

332
00:13:31,269 --> 00:13:32,937
Before that film,

333
00:13:33,021 --> 00:13:34,814
he mostly did lighthearted rom-coms

334
00:13:34,897 --> 00:13:37,400
or comedy films.

335
00:13:37,483 --> 00:13:41,112
That was his first serious drama role.

336
00:13:41,195 --> 00:13:42,030
Right.

337
00:13:42,113 --> 00:13:43,740
After I watched that,

338
00:13:43,823 --> 00:13:46,451
I became a huge fan of Nicolas Cage.

339
00:13:46,659 --> 00:13:51,414
I wanted to be an actor
who could act like that.

340
00:13:51,497 --> 00:13:53,166
It became clear to me.

341
00:13:53,249 --> 00:13:54,959
My dream was to be an actor,

342
00:13:55,043 --> 00:13:57,253
but the type of actor I wanted to be,

343
00:13:57,337 --> 00:13:58,963
the characters I wanted to play,

344
00:13:59,047 --> 00:14:02,925
became clear after I watched that film.

345
00:14:03,217 --> 00:14:05,178
- Your dream became clearer.
- Exactly.

346
00:14:05,261 --> 00:14:07,430
Then, who do you think

347
00:14:07,513 --> 00:14:10,892
is the best actor of all time?

348
00:14:11,392 --> 00:14:14,187
- Your father, Kim Yong-geon,
- Okay.

349
00:14:14,270 --> 00:14:16,272
or Nicolas Cage?

350
00:14:16,356 --> 00:14:17,690
It's Robert De Niro.

351
00:14:22,487 --> 00:14:23,821
Without a doubt?

352
00:14:23,905 --> 00:14:26,032
Yes, I think Robert De Niro is number one.

353
00:14:26,115 --> 00:14:28,117
Which of Robert De Niro's roles
inspired you?

354
00:14:28,409 --> 00:14:29,702
- There are too many.
- There are.

355
00:14:29,786 --> 00:14:30,953
Him in <i>The Godfather 2</i>.

356
00:14:31,371 --> 00:14:34,123
His role in <i>Mean Streets</i>

357
00:14:34,207 --> 00:14:35,958
- and <i>Taxi Driver</i>.
- I see.

358
00:14:36,459 --> 00:14:39,545
I know they're all old films, but still.

359
00:14:39,629 --> 00:14:40,797
Who's your role model?

360
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:43,633
- Robert De Niro is my role model.
- I see.

361
00:14:44,384 --> 00:14:47,011
Today, we're talking
about your dream as an actor.

362
00:14:47,095 --> 00:14:48,429
I read that you starred

363
00:14:48,721 --> 00:14:51,182
in three films that drew
over ten million admissions.

364
00:14:51,265 --> 00:14:54,227
<i>ALONG WITH THE GODS</i> 1 AND 2, <i>ASSASSINATION</i>
Three films.

365
00:14:54,310 --> 00:14:55,603
When you achieved that,

366
00:14:55,686 --> 00:14:57,146
did you consider that
as having achieved your dream?

367
00:14:57,230 --> 00:14:58,815
Or did your first big hit

368
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:00,817
make you feel like you've achieved it?

369
00:15:05,446 --> 00:15:06,614
No.

370
00:15:06,697 --> 00:15:08,950
I wouldn't say I achieved my dream.

371
00:15:09,700 --> 00:15:11,536
I don't think

372
00:15:12,370 --> 00:15:14,956
it's something
that can be measured in numbers.

373
00:15:15,498 --> 00:15:18,251
Those are just milestones
along the journey

374
00:15:18,334 --> 00:15:20,545
of moving towards your dream.

375
00:15:21,170 --> 00:15:24,006
At what point would you say
that you achieved your dream?

376
00:15:24,799 --> 00:15:25,925
I don't know.

377
00:15:27,176 --> 00:15:28,261
I never

378
00:15:28,719 --> 00:15:32,265
thought about it like that.

379
00:15:32,348 --> 00:15:34,809
People say
that you want to be a prolific actor.

380
00:15:34,892 --> 00:15:35,893
I do, actually.

381
00:15:35,977 --> 00:15:37,520
My goal regarding that

382
00:15:37,603 --> 00:15:40,648
- is to star in 100 films.
- Right.

383
00:15:40,815 --> 00:15:42,692
That would be my first mission

384
00:15:42,775 --> 00:15:45,361
on the way to reaching my dream.

385
00:15:45,486 --> 00:15:47,405
- Your first goal is to be in 100 films.
- Yes.

386
00:15:47,488 --> 00:15:48,614
How far along are you?

387
00:15:48,698 --> 00:15:50,658
- I think I'm about halfway.
- I see.

388
00:15:50,741 --> 00:15:53,995
Since we're talking about acting,
let me ask you this.

389
00:15:54,078 --> 00:15:55,663
From your perspective,

390
00:15:55,746 --> 00:15:59,292
you're still on your way
to achieving your dream.

391
00:15:59,417 --> 00:16:01,419
But is there a scene of yours

392
00:16:01,502 --> 00:16:04,046
where you think you did an amazing job?

393
00:16:04,922 --> 00:16:07,258
- Something you'd want to brag about.
- Well...

394
00:16:07,925 --> 00:16:09,427
Even with books,

395
00:16:09,510 --> 00:16:12,555
sometimes a sentence of a book
is more powerful than the book itself.

396
00:16:12,680 --> 00:16:15,808
Give me just one scene
of a film you were in

397
00:16:17,101 --> 00:16:19,770
that makes you think,
"I was amazing in that."

398
00:16:21,814 --> 00:16:23,691
- I don't know.
- You can do it.

399
00:16:23,774 --> 00:16:25,651
It's hard to pick one.

400
00:16:26,277 --> 00:16:29,489
- Which one...
<i>- Take Off</i> was amazing, too.

401
00:16:29,572 --> 00:16:31,824
- The airport scene in <i>Take Off</i>
- Right.

402
00:16:31,908 --> 00:16:33,910
was very inspired.

403
00:16:33,993 --> 00:16:35,203
In <i>Tunnel,</i>

404
00:16:35,286 --> 00:16:37,371
there's a scene where Bae Doo-na asks me

405
00:16:37,455 --> 00:16:38,956
how I am over the radio

406
00:16:39,040 --> 00:16:40,750
and as I am listening to the radio,

407
00:16:40,833 --> 00:16:43,878
I am missing my wife.

408
00:16:43,961 --> 00:16:47,048
That's a scene that comes to my mind.

409
00:16:47,131 --> 00:16:49,550
In <i>Assassination</i>, there's a scene

410
00:16:49,634 --> 00:16:53,179
HE COULDN'T PICK ONE
where I get shot by someone.

411
00:16:53,262 --> 00:16:55,473
BECAUSE THERE WERE TOO MANY
In that scene,

412
00:16:55,556 --> 00:16:57,808
the way I reacted to the gunshot

413
00:16:57,892 --> 00:17:00,978
is a scene that I was happy with.

414
00:17:01,437 --> 00:17:04,106
The scenes that stay with you
even after a long time

415
00:17:04,190 --> 00:17:06,651
- are not just about skills or technique.
- Right.

416
00:17:06,734 --> 00:17:08,486
In the chasing scene in <i>The Chaser</i>,

417
00:17:08,569 --> 00:17:10,738
I stumble on a manhole cover.

418
00:17:10,821 --> 00:17:13,991
That wasn't planned. It was an accident.

419
00:17:14,116 --> 00:17:17,203
But I got up immediately
and started running again.

420
00:17:17,620 --> 00:17:22,625
<i>THE CHASER</i> (2008), DIRECTED BY NA HONG-JIN

421
00:17:23,084 --> 00:17:24,669
If you watch that scene,

422
00:17:24,752 --> 00:17:26,128
<i>when I fall down,</i>

423
00:17:26,212 --> 00:17:28,297
<i>the camera loses focus to stop filming.</i>

424
00:17:28,381 --> 00:17:29,423
<i>The camera pans down slightly,</i>

425
00:17:29,507 --> 00:17:30,591
<i>but as I start running again,</i>

426
00:17:30,675 --> 00:17:33,135
<i>it focuses back on me.</i>

427
00:17:33,219 --> 00:17:34,845
<i>It happens within a few seconds.</i>

428
00:17:34,929 --> 00:17:37,056
The director decided to keep all that.

429
00:17:37,723 --> 00:17:39,475
It's a scene in the film

430
00:17:39,559 --> 00:17:43,062
that feels raw and real.

431
00:17:43,145 --> 00:17:46,232
It gives the audience that feeling.

432
00:17:46,524 --> 00:17:49,694
Have you ever used
your acting skills in real life?

433
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:51,070
Be honest.

434
00:17:54,323 --> 00:17:55,866
I feel like I have.

435
00:17:55,950 --> 00:17:57,743
But I can't think of a specific moment.

436
00:17:58,286 --> 00:17:59,704
Are you using it right now?

437
00:17:59,787 --> 00:18:01,289
I guess I am.

438
00:18:01,372 --> 00:18:03,541
But aren't we all acting in real life?

439
00:18:04,625 --> 00:18:08,045
Everyone acts in real life,
if you think about it.

440
00:18:09,589 --> 00:18:11,173
FOOTNOTE: BAD EXAMPLE

441
00:18:11,257 --> 00:18:12,633
What kind of character
are you acting right now?

442
00:18:12,717 --> 00:18:16,304
- Right now, I'm here on <i>Hodong's Bookshop</i>
- Right.

443
00:18:16,512 --> 00:18:20,433
playing the role of Kim Sung-hoon
talking about Ha Jung-woo.

444
00:18:20,516 --> 00:18:21,934
- Even though you feel shy,
- Yes.

445
00:18:22,018 --> 00:18:23,185
you act like you don't.

446
00:18:23,269 --> 00:18:24,645
- That's right.
- Yes.

447
00:18:24,729 --> 00:18:27,356
That comes naturally to me now.

448
00:18:28,065 --> 00:18:30,443
When did your dream
of being a director start?

449
00:18:30,735 --> 00:18:32,987
- When I was in sixth grade,
- Yes?

450
00:18:33,070 --> 00:18:36,032
I watched <i>Modern Times</i> by Charlie Chaplin.

451
00:18:36,115 --> 00:18:40,411
<i>Charlie Chaplin</i>
<i>was an actor and a director.</i>

452
00:18:40,494 --> 00:18:42,163
<i>"How did he do that?</i>

453
00:18:42,371 --> 00:18:44,540
Direct a film and also act in it?

454
00:18:44,624 --> 00:18:46,083
I want to be like him."

455
00:18:46,167 --> 00:18:48,044
That's what I thought.

456
00:18:48,169 --> 00:18:49,754
When I look at the timeline,

457
00:18:49,837 --> 00:18:51,797
after <i>The Berlin File</i>,

458
00:18:51,881 --> 00:18:56,135
you started making <i>Fasten Your Seatbelt,</i>

459
00:18:56,218 --> 00:18:57,970
- starring Jung Kyung-ho.
- Yes.

460
00:18:58,179 --> 00:18:59,680
Your directed works are
<i>Fasten Your Seatbelt,</i>

461
00:18:59,764 --> 00:19:04,060
<i>Chronicles of a Blood Merchant,</i>
<i>Lobby,</i> and <i>The People Upstairs.</i>

462
00:19:04,602 --> 00:19:07,188
I watched
all of the films you've directed.

463
00:19:07,271 --> 00:19:09,982
In them, there's satire
about the duality of humans,

464
00:19:10,107 --> 00:19:12,151
- but there's also your love for humanity.
- Yes.

465
00:19:12,234 --> 00:19:14,737
- That's what the films have in common.
- Right.

466
00:19:14,820 --> 00:19:18,616
I think those are the two things
I always have in mind.

467
00:19:19,533 --> 00:19:20,826
Humans...

468
00:19:20,951 --> 00:19:22,995
I'm just interested in
humanity as a whole.

469
00:19:23,079 --> 00:19:24,872
Humans the way they are.

470
00:19:24,997 --> 00:19:27,792
Humans have many sides to them.

471
00:19:28,292 --> 00:19:30,127
People act one way with someone

472
00:19:30,211 --> 00:19:32,088
and another way with someone else.

473
00:19:32,171 --> 00:19:36,133
I'm interested
in that multifaceted nature.

474
00:19:36,509 --> 00:19:39,929
So I wrote and directed
films that are about that.

475
00:19:40,012 --> 00:19:42,473
They're all satires
about the human duality.

476
00:19:42,556 --> 00:19:43,974
You have a passion, but...

477
00:19:44,183 --> 00:19:46,268
You starred in
three ten-million-admission films.

478
00:19:46,352 --> 00:19:47,186
Yes.

479
00:19:47,269 --> 00:19:48,437
As an actor,

480
00:19:48,521 --> 00:19:50,231
- you drew so many viewers.
- Yes.

481
00:19:50,314 --> 00:19:53,150
- Compared to how you were as an actor,
- Yes?

482
00:19:53,234 --> 00:19:56,028
people weren't exactly wowed

483
00:19:56,112 --> 00:19:58,155
- by the films you directed.
- No.

484
00:19:58,906 --> 00:20:01,117
- So--
- Would the total be ten million?

485
00:20:01,200 --> 00:20:02,910
Oh, not even close.

486
00:20:02,993 --> 00:20:04,245
- Not even close?
- No.

487
00:20:04,370 --> 00:20:07,289
The four films probably drew
around two million in total.

488
00:20:09,417 --> 00:20:12,169
It isn't easy. It really isn't.

489
00:20:12,962 --> 00:20:14,338
I'm wondering if my taste

490
00:20:14,422 --> 00:20:17,758
and the subject matters
I want to talk about

491
00:20:17,842 --> 00:20:20,428
in my films as a director

492
00:20:20,511 --> 00:20:24,223
do not appeal to a wide audience.

493
00:20:24,306 --> 00:20:25,307
I just...

494
00:20:26,183 --> 00:20:28,018
I think about what story to tell.

495
00:20:28,102 --> 00:20:30,521
What story can I tell

496
00:20:30,604 --> 00:20:32,440
that everyone will relate to

497
00:20:32,523 --> 00:20:34,191
and make them want to

498
00:20:34,275 --> 00:20:36,777
talk about the film with each other?

499
00:20:36,861 --> 00:20:40,573
That's all I think about as a director.

500
00:20:41,073 --> 00:20:42,283
I'd just walk and think.

501
00:20:43,075 --> 00:20:44,118
I see.

502
00:20:44,618 --> 00:20:46,996
I would walk any chance I got.

503
00:20:47,079 --> 00:20:48,122
- Wait a minute.
- Yes?

504
00:20:48,205 --> 00:20:50,583
I saw that you wrote a book.

505
00:20:50,666 --> 00:20:52,126
- I did.
- Hold on. I have it.

506
00:20:52,209 --> 00:20:53,294
Please give me a moment.

507
00:20:53,377 --> 00:20:55,212
I saw it somewhere here.

508
00:20:55,629 --> 00:20:57,548
It's a good book.

509
00:20:57,840 --> 00:20:59,467
Somewhere here.

510
00:20:59,717 --> 00:21:01,594
- Here it is.
- I see.

511
00:21:01,719 --> 00:21:03,220
<i>- Walking Man, Ha Jung-woo</i>.
- Yes.

512
00:21:03,554 --> 00:21:04,805
<i>- Walking Man, Ha Jung-woo</i>.
- Yes.

513
00:21:04,889 --> 00:21:06,432
ACTOR HA JUNG-WOO ON
THE PHILOSOPHY OF WALKING AND LIFE

514
00:21:06,515 --> 00:21:07,641
It was a good read.

515
00:21:07,725 --> 00:21:09,059
- Thank you.
- It was.

516
00:21:09,226 --> 00:21:12,062
- This was published in 2018.
- Right.

517
00:21:12,146 --> 00:21:13,314
What is it about?

518
00:21:14,607 --> 00:21:17,610
This book is about walking.

519
00:21:17,860 --> 00:21:19,361
It's about why walking is good for you

520
00:21:19,445 --> 00:21:22,573
and how walking has affected my life.

521
00:21:22,823 --> 00:21:24,533
All of these photos

522
00:21:24,617 --> 00:21:27,077
were taken by me with my phone.

523
00:21:28,037 --> 00:21:30,831
- I remember them.
- When I read it, I was impressed.

524
00:21:32,291 --> 00:21:34,835
- Walking is really...
- Yes?

525
00:21:35,461 --> 00:21:37,922
It's really, really important.

526
00:21:38,005 --> 00:21:40,633
You said you walked 100,000
to 150,000 steps in a day.

527
00:21:40,716 --> 00:21:42,051
Not 150,000 steps. About 100,000 steps.

528
00:21:42,134 --> 00:21:43,761
Okay, 100,000 steps, but...

529
00:21:43,844 --> 00:21:45,554
A member of my walking club

530
00:21:45,638 --> 00:21:47,723
once walked 160,000 steps.

531
00:21:47,807 --> 00:21:49,350
How long would that even take?

532
00:21:49,433 --> 00:21:50,893
You'd have to walk for over 24 hours.

533
00:21:50,976 --> 00:21:52,561
- With no break?
- Exactly.

534
00:21:52,812 --> 00:21:54,522
When I walked 100,000 steps,

535
00:21:54,605 --> 00:21:56,857
it took a little over 20 hours.

536
00:21:56,941 --> 00:21:58,943
So if you want to get to 160,000 steps,

537
00:21:59,026 --> 00:22:00,653
you'd have to run half the time.

538
00:22:00,736 --> 00:22:02,655
Even if you walked for 24 hours,

539
00:22:02,738 --> 00:22:04,740
- you wouldn't get there.
- No.

540
00:22:04,824 --> 00:22:07,701
It takes an hour and a half
to walk 10,000 steps.

541
00:22:07,785 --> 00:22:09,912
An hour and 20 minutes if you walk fast.

542
00:22:09,995 --> 00:22:11,205
- We're in Yeongdeungpo.
- Right.

543
00:22:11,288 --> 00:22:12,331
Did you walk here?

544
00:22:12,414 --> 00:22:13,707
No, I came here by car.

545
00:22:15,042 --> 00:22:19,004
I once walked to Noryangjin Fish Market,

546
00:22:19,088 --> 00:22:21,298
bought some fish, and walked back home.

547
00:22:21,382 --> 00:22:22,299
From near Namsan?

548
00:22:22,383 --> 00:22:23,843
- I lived in Jamwon-dong then.
- I see.

549
00:22:23,926 --> 00:22:25,052
From Hannam Bridge,

550
00:22:25,135 --> 00:22:26,971
I walked there along the park

551
00:22:27,054 --> 00:22:29,348
and walked back after buying fish.

552
00:22:29,431 --> 00:22:30,516
A TOTAL OF 20KM TO BUY FISH

553
00:22:30,599 --> 00:22:32,476
You must have
a lot of people you walk with.

554
00:22:32,560 --> 00:22:35,145
Yes. We have a lot of meetings
when we're making a film.

555
00:22:35,229 --> 00:22:36,272
Whenever we hit a wall,

556
00:22:36,355 --> 00:22:39,650
the directing department and I go out
to walk and talk all day.

557
00:22:40,192 --> 00:22:43,153
And eventually,
we would find a breakthrough.

558
00:22:44,363 --> 00:22:47,783
I think that proves
that everybody has ideas,

559
00:22:47,867 --> 00:22:49,493
but their brains freeze up.

560
00:22:49,577 --> 00:22:52,496
Or they feel too impatient.

561
00:22:52,580 --> 00:22:54,957
If you relax a little bit,

562
00:22:55,165 --> 00:22:58,002
ideas, thoughts, and realizations

563
00:22:58,085 --> 00:22:59,837
come to you naturally.

564
00:23:00,170 --> 00:23:03,299
And for that, you have to walk a lot.

565
00:23:03,382 --> 00:23:04,425
- Right.
- Yes.

566
00:23:07,011 --> 00:23:09,513
You're aware that I'm very old, right?

567
00:23:09,597 --> 00:23:10,764
Yes, I am.

568
00:23:10,848 --> 00:23:12,349
I'm pretty old.

569
00:23:13,142 --> 00:23:15,519
This has never been
part of my skillset before,

570
00:23:15,895 --> 00:23:17,396
but do you smell heaven?

571
00:23:17,479 --> 00:23:18,772
- Heaven?
- Yes.

572
00:23:20,232 --> 00:23:21,734
- There's a saying.
- Yes?

573
00:23:21,817 --> 00:23:23,193
- It's one of my favorites.
- Okay.

574
00:23:23,611 --> 00:23:26,447
"A happy family is but an earlier heaven."

575
00:23:27,072 --> 00:23:28,198
- Okay.
- Family...

576
00:23:30,326 --> 00:23:32,161
I think I know what you mean.

577
00:23:33,370 --> 00:23:34,496
Are you happy?

578
00:23:34,580 --> 00:23:35,623
Yes, I am.

579
00:23:38,834 --> 00:23:40,377
So that's what you were smelling.

580
00:23:42,338 --> 00:23:45,049
THE NEWS ABOUT HIM DATING WENT VIRAL
I read the news.

581
00:23:45,132 --> 00:23:47,843
- From our perspective--
- You were probably curious.

582
00:23:48,010 --> 00:23:51,513
There are many joys in life,
but this is one of them.

583
00:23:52,431 --> 00:23:54,058
- If you like to do something,
- Yes.

584
00:23:54,141 --> 00:23:56,769
and there's someone you like and love,

585
00:23:56,852 --> 00:23:58,604
it's nice when you help them
find joy in what you like too.

586
00:23:58,687 --> 00:23:59,980
- It's very nice.
- Right.

587
00:24:00,064 --> 00:24:01,941
You can walk together,

588
00:24:02,024 --> 00:24:03,275
- enjoy the view,
- Right.

589
00:24:03,359 --> 00:24:05,444
- and enjoy looking at her too.
- Right.

590
00:24:05,569 --> 00:24:07,196
Do you walk together or not?

591
00:24:09,281 --> 00:24:10,824
She doesn't enjoy walking.

592
00:24:12,493 --> 00:24:15,287
She doesn't. It's a shame.

593
00:24:15,871 --> 00:24:18,499
I've dreamt of something like that.

594
00:24:18,666 --> 00:24:20,209
"I want to walk

595
00:24:20,918 --> 00:24:22,628
the whole world with someone.

596
00:24:23,170 --> 00:24:25,214
I want to conquer

597
00:24:25,297 --> 00:24:27,341
all of the hiking trails together,
one by one."

598
00:24:27,424 --> 00:24:28,884
But she doesn't enjoy walking at all.

599
00:24:29,927 --> 00:24:32,638
So one time, we took a trip to Hawaii.

600
00:24:32,721 --> 00:24:34,056
There, we went on a walk.

601
00:24:34,640 --> 00:24:37,351
We walked for about two hours

602
00:24:37,434 --> 00:24:39,269
before she gave up entirely.

603
00:24:40,270 --> 00:24:41,772
- A trip to Hawaii?
- Yes.

604
00:24:43,065 --> 00:24:44,108
Just the two of you?

605
00:24:44,191 --> 00:24:47,152
Of course. What else would I do?
Bring my parents too?

606
00:24:48,821 --> 00:24:50,823
I didn't expect to
get these answers so easily.

607
00:24:51,991 --> 00:24:53,283
All right.

608
00:24:53,367 --> 00:24:54,868
You must've been surprised
when you saw the first article on it.

609
00:24:55,160 --> 00:24:57,621
Of course, because...

610
00:24:58,205 --> 00:25:00,499
Is it necessary to share my private life?

611
00:25:00,582 --> 00:25:03,794
I don't know
what's going to happen in my life.

612
00:25:03,961 --> 00:25:07,047
So I don't see a need to announce
everything going on in my life.

613
00:25:07,131 --> 00:25:10,050
I know that gossip can be fun.

614
00:25:10,134 --> 00:25:11,760
Especially about celebrities.

615
00:25:11,844 --> 00:25:13,679
But celebrities are people too.

616
00:25:13,762 --> 00:25:15,639
Just like other people,

617
00:25:15,723 --> 00:25:17,391
getting married

618
00:25:17,474 --> 00:25:19,685
and dating people

619
00:25:19,768 --> 00:25:21,353
- is not something to take lightly.
- Right.

620
00:25:21,437 --> 00:25:23,272
It's never a certain thing.

621
00:25:23,355 --> 00:25:26,525
But when rumor-based articles come out

622
00:25:26,608 --> 00:25:29,069
before the people involved
have a chance to say anything,

623
00:25:29,236 --> 00:25:33,657
what are the people involved
supposed to do then?

624
00:25:33,824 --> 00:25:36,535
If we don't confirm our relationship,

625
00:25:36,618 --> 00:25:38,454
more rumor-based articles like that

626
00:25:38,537 --> 00:25:40,622
- would come out.
- Right.

627
00:25:40,706 --> 00:25:43,167
It's not like

628
00:25:43,375 --> 00:25:45,210
- dating someone is weird.
- Right.

629
00:25:45,294 --> 00:25:47,087
It's just awkward to talk about.

630
00:25:48,338 --> 00:25:51,008
So we just decided to confirm it,

631
00:25:51,091 --> 00:25:52,801
and we did.

632
00:25:52,885 --> 00:25:54,845
A lot of people congratulated us.

633
00:25:54,928 --> 00:25:56,847
So, that's all.

634
00:25:56,930 --> 00:25:58,724
People around you

635
00:25:58,807 --> 00:26:01,268
- and most of the general public
- Yes.

636
00:26:01,351 --> 00:26:04,063
- would be happy for you.
- That's right.

637
00:26:04,188 --> 00:26:06,440
So I think we can skip this question

638
00:26:06,523 --> 00:26:08,484
- about how you guys met.
- All right.

639
00:26:08,567 --> 00:26:10,861
- I think I can do that.
- All right.

640
00:26:10,944 --> 00:26:13,155
It's just happy news.

641
00:26:14,490 --> 00:26:18,744
IT IS ALSO GOOD TO LOVE,
BECAUSE LOVE IS DIFFICULT

642
00:26:18,827 --> 00:26:21,163
FOR ONE HUMAN BEING
TO LOVE ANOTHER HUMAN BEING

643
00:26:21,246 --> 00:26:24,625
THAT IS PERHAPS THE MOST DIFFICULT TASK
THAT HAS BEEN ENTRUSTED TO US

644
00:26:24,708 --> 00:26:26,168
FROM <i>LETTERS TO A YOUNG POET</i>

645
00:26:27,211 --> 00:26:30,422
HA JUNG-WOO'S LIFE CHOICES
We make a lot of choices in life.

646
00:26:30,756 --> 00:26:32,466
What's the best choice you made?

647
00:26:35,886 --> 00:26:37,763
What choice do you regret the most?

648
00:26:37,971 --> 00:26:39,640
Which one first?

649
00:26:39,723 --> 00:26:41,350
- What I regret the most.
- Okay.

650
00:26:41,642 --> 00:26:43,852
- What comes to your mind?
- Bad investments.

651
00:26:46,480 --> 00:26:49,024
Some bad investments.

652
00:26:49,817 --> 00:26:52,277
It's not just about financial investments.

653
00:26:52,361 --> 00:26:54,655
- Investing time is a big deal, too.
- Right.

654
00:26:54,738 --> 00:26:57,533
- Since you mentioned investments,
- Yes?

655
00:26:57,783 --> 00:26:59,660
we can talk about your talents.

656
00:26:59,743 --> 00:27:01,912
Things you like and things you're good at

657
00:27:01,995 --> 00:27:03,288
- are not the same.
- Right.

658
00:27:03,372 --> 00:27:06,416
For most people,
there's a gap between those two.

659
00:27:06,500 --> 00:27:09,503
For example, although you like directing,

660
00:27:09,586 --> 00:27:11,463
- it's hard to be good at it.
- Right.

661
00:27:11,547 --> 00:27:14,633
- Then, rather than pursuing directing,
- Yes?

662
00:27:14,716 --> 00:27:17,302
you could've invested more in your acting.

663
00:27:17,386 --> 00:27:18,512
Do you have regrets like that?

664
00:27:18,595 --> 00:27:20,097
Not at all.

665
00:27:20,305 --> 00:27:22,432
I know it's going to work out in the end.

666
00:27:22,516 --> 00:27:25,519
Now is the time
to go through the whole process.

667
00:27:25,853 --> 00:27:28,230
Rome wasn't built in a day.

668
00:27:28,313 --> 00:27:30,858
If I truly want to be a good director,

669
00:27:30,941 --> 00:27:33,986
I know I have to go through this process.

670
00:27:34,069 --> 00:27:36,321
So, for what I'm going through now,

671
00:27:36,405 --> 00:27:38,365
I have no regrets.

672
00:27:38,949 --> 00:27:41,118
Not even a bit.

673
00:27:41,660 --> 00:27:43,453
I don't regret anything.

674
00:27:43,537 --> 00:27:46,748
You can't judge a person
based on short-term results.

675
00:27:46,832 --> 00:27:50,043
But people like to do that.

676
00:27:50,210 --> 00:27:52,462
Like I mentioned before,
you can't judge someone's life

677
00:27:52,546 --> 00:27:55,215
purely based on how many times
they retook the college entrance exams.

678
00:27:55,299 --> 00:27:58,468
I think you'll see once time has passed.

679
00:27:58,594 --> 00:28:00,470
- All of this becomes your potential,
- Right.

680
00:28:00,554 --> 00:28:01,930
- and your energy.
- Yes.

681
00:28:02,014 --> 00:28:04,349
- It makes you grow.
- Right.

682
00:28:04,683 --> 00:28:08,854
The relationship between
Rilke and Rodin is very well-known.

683
00:28:09,271 --> 00:28:11,148
Back when Rilke wasn't famous,

684
00:28:11,815 --> 00:28:13,358
he asked Rodin,

685
00:28:13,525 --> 00:28:14,902
"How should I live?"

686
00:28:15,485 --> 00:28:17,154
Rodin answered,

687
00:28:17,529 --> 00:28:18,697
"You must work.

688
00:28:18,780 --> 00:28:21,283
And you must have patience."

689
00:28:21,700 --> 00:28:24,077
This sounds simple enough,

690
00:28:24,620 --> 00:28:26,872
but this had a huge influence

691
00:28:26,955 --> 00:28:28,790
- on Rilke's mindset as an artist.
- Right.

692
00:28:28,916 --> 00:28:30,083
What is patience?

693
00:28:30,167 --> 00:28:33,045
It's pain that you should be grateful for.

694
00:28:35,255 --> 00:28:37,049
I think that's basing it
purely on the result.

695
00:28:38,133 --> 00:28:41,345
Saying that patience
is something to be grateful for

696
00:28:41,428 --> 00:28:44,223
is focusing on the result
that the patience brought.

697
00:28:44,306 --> 00:28:46,767
It's retrospective.

698
00:28:46,850 --> 00:28:49,269
But if you're feeling grateful

699
00:28:49,353 --> 00:28:52,064
during that time of patience,

700
00:28:52,147 --> 00:28:54,483
you'd be an incredibly admirable person.

701
00:28:54,942 --> 00:28:56,610
- Feeling grateful during that time?
- Yes.

702
00:28:57,361 --> 00:29:00,739
That is the ideal way to live, actually.

703
00:29:01,615 --> 00:29:03,075
I've also thought about this.

704
00:29:03,158 --> 00:29:04,451
When I was an athlete,

705
00:29:04,534 --> 00:29:06,703
- I didn't know where the end was.
- I see.

706
00:29:07,079 --> 00:29:11,124
It's like you're trying to
climb in the dark.

707
00:29:11,375 --> 00:29:13,835
You fall down and get up again.

708
00:29:14,253 --> 00:29:17,547
You could push yourself
ten, twenty times beyond your limits,

709
00:29:17,631 --> 00:29:19,591
and give up
ten meters before the finish line.

710
00:29:19,675 --> 00:29:20,550
Right.

711
00:29:20,634 --> 00:29:22,302
- Because you don't know where it ends.
- Right.

712
00:29:22,386 --> 00:29:23,971
That whole process is patience.

713
00:29:24,054 --> 00:29:26,932
So it's hard to be grateful
for all that pain.

714
00:29:27,015 --> 00:29:27,891
That's true.

715
00:29:28,558 --> 00:29:29,559
How would you know?

716
00:29:29,643 --> 00:29:31,979
That's right. You don't know.

717
00:29:32,771 --> 00:29:35,482
You wrote in this book

718
00:29:35,565 --> 00:29:38,860
- about walking from Seoul to Haenam,
- Right.

719
00:29:38,944 --> 00:29:40,612
- and you made a documentary about it too.
- I did.

720
00:29:40,696 --> 00:29:42,114
- You walked over 500km.
- Yes.

721
00:29:42,281 --> 00:29:44,157
When you got there in the end,

722
00:29:44,241 --> 00:29:47,995
you mentioned that you thought
you'd feel super happy,

723
00:29:48,078 --> 00:29:50,289
- that you expected to feel a great joy
- Right.

724
00:29:50,372 --> 00:29:53,500
- after achieving such a big thing.
- Yes.

725
00:29:53,583 --> 00:29:56,920
- But on the contrary, you felt empty.
- That's right.

726
00:29:57,504 --> 00:29:58,755
- That's true.
- Right.

727
00:29:59,339 --> 00:30:01,425
The process was a lot of fun.

728
00:30:01,508 --> 00:30:04,219
The process of getting there

729
00:30:04,303 --> 00:30:05,762
was the meaningful part.

730
00:30:05,846 --> 00:30:07,014
But once I got there,

731
00:30:08,348 --> 00:30:10,767
I didn't really feel anything.

732
00:30:11,685 --> 00:30:14,896
I felt so empty inside in a way,

733
00:30:15,022 --> 00:30:16,940
that I just went back home that night.

734
00:30:17,024 --> 00:30:19,276
- I heard.
- I felt so deflated.

735
00:30:19,401 --> 00:30:21,361
And when I got home

736
00:30:21,570 --> 00:30:23,655
and looked back on the trip,

737
00:30:23,989 --> 00:30:26,825
it wasn't the sense of achievement
of making it there,

738
00:30:26,950 --> 00:30:30,287
<i>but the time I spent</i>
<i>on the road getting there</i>

739
00:30:30,370 --> 00:30:31,788
<i>that came to my mind.</i>

740
00:30:32,998 --> 00:30:34,875
- The more time goes by,
- Yes.

741
00:30:34,958 --> 00:30:36,752
- from time to time in your life,
- Right.

742
00:30:36,835 --> 00:30:38,545
- that time comes to your mind.
- Yes.

743
00:30:38,628 --> 00:30:41,340
The end result doesn't nourish the person.

744
00:30:41,423 --> 00:30:43,383
The process does.

745
00:30:43,467 --> 00:30:45,844
- That's what makes you grow.
- I see.

746
00:30:47,888 --> 00:30:50,098
YOU ARE SO YOUNG

747
00:30:50,182 --> 00:30:54,227
DON'T SEARCH FOR THE ANSWERS,
WHICH COULD NOT BE GIVEN TO YOU NOW,

748
00:30:54,311 --> 00:30:56,730
BECAUSE YOU WOULD NOT BE ABLE TO LIVE THEM

749
00:30:56,813 --> 00:31:02,736
SAND THE POINT IS TO LIVE EVERYTHING,
LIVE THE QUESTIONS NOW

750
00:31:02,819 --> 00:31:05,030
PERHAPS THEN, SOMEDAY FAR IN THE FUTURE

751
00:31:05,113 --> 00:31:08,867
YOU WILL GRADUALLY, WITHOUT EVEN
NOTICING IT, LIVE YOUR WAY INTO THE ANSWER

752
00:31:08,950 --> 00:31:10,494
FROM <i>LETTERS TO A YOUNG POET</i>

753
00:31:10,577 --> 00:31:12,996
- You returned to a series after 19 years.
- Yes.

754
00:31:13,080 --> 00:31:15,165
<i>- Mad Concrete Dreams.</i>
- Yes.

755
00:31:15,248 --> 00:31:16,500
What's this series about?

756
00:31:17,209 --> 00:31:19,544
It's about owning a building,
which I guess I do.

757
00:31:20,629 --> 00:31:24,383
Anyway, my character is the protagonist.

758
00:31:24,674 --> 00:31:26,927
He goes from being poor
to owning a building.

759
00:31:27,010 --> 00:31:28,053
- The process of getting there.
- Right.

760
00:31:28,637 --> 00:31:30,180
I think it's relatable.

761
00:31:30,263 --> 00:31:32,140
It isn't about
a rich man buying a building.

762
00:31:32,224 --> 00:31:34,226
This person is working to get paid,

763
00:31:34,768 --> 00:31:36,019
but he quits his job,

764
00:31:36,103 --> 00:31:39,272
takes his retirement fund
and all his life's savings,

765
00:31:39,856 --> 00:31:41,108
and buys a tiny building.

766
00:31:41,650 --> 00:31:44,152
- I see.
- He gets bank loans too.

767
00:31:44,486 --> 00:31:46,071
But this series is about

768
00:31:46,655 --> 00:31:48,490
- what he goes through
- Yes.

769
00:31:48,573 --> 00:31:50,117
and what he loses

770
00:31:50,200 --> 00:31:52,744
on his way to becoming a building owner.

771
00:31:53,245 --> 00:31:54,454
It's a story about that.

772
00:31:54,538 --> 00:31:55,789
- Gains and losses.
- Yes.

773
00:31:55,997 --> 00:31:58,667
- This is a series made for TV.
- That's right.

774
00:31:58,750 --> 00:32:01,294
It must've taken courage
to return after 19 years.

775
00:32:02,504 --> 00:32:05,549
I personally don't feel like
starring in a TV series

776
00:32:05,632 --> 00:32:07,217
is bold or takes courage.

777
00:32:07,634 --> 00:32:09,678
But I did return after 19 years,

778
00:32:09,761 --> 00:32:11,346
and so much has changed.

779
00:32:11,430 --> 00:32:12,681
- The environment?
- Yes.

780
00:32:12,806 --> 00:32:15,183
- First of all, the shooting time.
- Right.

781
00:32:15,267 --> 00:32:18,854
They stick to the fixed shooting time.

782
00:32:18,937 --> 00:32:20,897
Twelve hours per day.

783
00:32:20,981 --> 00:32:25,986
We're legally required to shoot
52 hours maximum per week.

784
00:32:26,069 --> 00:32:28,029
And there are no last-minute scripts.

785
00:32:28,113 --> 00:32:30,907
Right, I got the full script
before we started shooting.

786
00:32:30,991 --> 00:32:32,492
For the full 12 episodes.

787
00:32:32,576 --> 00:32:35,078
Anyway, it was
very different and interesting.

788
00:32:36,705 --> 00:32:38,748
- You're an actor and a director.
- Right.

789
00:32:38,832 --> 00:32:41,001
- You're also a writer.
- Right.

790
00:32:41,084 --> 00:32:43,044
- On top of that, a painter.
- Yes.

791
00:32:43,128 --> 00:32:44,838
How did you start painting?

792
00:32:44,921 --> 00:32:46,465
HOW DID HE START PAINTING?

793
00:32:48,091 --> 00:32:49,509
It's funny.

794
00:32:49,593 --> 00:32:53,054
After finishing college,
I didn't have much to do.

795
00:32:53,346 --> 00:32:54,973
I went to auditions

796
00:32:55,056 --> 00:32:56,808
and waited to hear back.

797
00:32:57,767 --> 00:33:00,687
I had a lot of free time in that period.

798
00:33:00,770 --> 00:33:02,230
- A lot of time.
- Right.

799
00:33:02,397 --> 00:33:05,150
I thought about
what I should do with that time.

800
00:33:05,233 --> 00:33:07,986
I wanted to do something productive.

801
00:33:08,069 --> 00:33:10,280
So I decided to paint.

802
00:33:10,906 --> 00:33:12,324
I went to a stationery store
in the neighborhood

803
00:33:12,699 --> 00:33:15,744
and bought a sketchbook,
4B pencils, and watercolors.

804
00:33:15,911 --> 00:33:17,287
And I started painting.

805
00:33:17,370 --> 00:33:18,580
Did you paint as a kid?

806
00:33:18,663 --> 00:33:20,957
I had art classes as a kid

807
00:33:21,041 --> 00:33:23,418
and even won contests in the area.

808
00:33:23,585 --> 00:33:26,505
When I started painting,
it soothed me, and time went fast.

809
00:33:26,588 --> 00:33:28,840
Time feels slower when you're young.

810
00:33:28,924 --> 00:33:30,258
So I liked it.

811
00:33:31,009 --> 00:33:35,555
Then I wanted to try painting
on a canvas instead of my sketchbook.

812
00:33:35,639 --> 00:33:38,266
So I went to a bigger stationery store.

813
00:33:38,350 --> 00:33:41,770
They recommended some paints,
and I kept painting with them.

814
00:33:42,020 --> 00:33:44,689
- I painted on bigger and bigger canvases.
- I see.

815
00:33:44,773 --> 00:33:46,233
You had an exhibition in New York.

816
00:33:46,316 --> 00:33:47,651
- Yes.
- In New York.

817
00:33:47,734 --> 00:33:49,027
You boldly went to New York.

818
00:33:49,110 --> 00:33:50,695
- Right.
- "Ha Jung-woo, the painter."

819
00:33:50,779 --> 00:33:51,863
You held an exhibition

820
00:33:51,947 --> 00:33:53,490
- and sold one painting.
- Yes.

821
00:33:53,573 --> 00:33:56,952
And the people working at the gallery
said, "Don't come to New York again."

822
00:33:57,118 --> 00:33:59,037
So that's what the story turned into.

823
00:34:00,330 --> 00:34:02,415
It became a whole drama.

824
00:34:02,624 --> 00:34:03,750
A big story.

825
00:34:03,833 --> 00:34:05,835
The people in New York cut you off.

826
00:34:06,753 --> 00:34:08,421
They were like, "Stay away."

827
00:34:08,588 --> 00:34:09,923
Can I give you the facts now?

828
00:34:11,258 --> 00:34:13,093
It was back in 2015.

829
00:34:13,176 --> 00:34:15,595
I held a solo exhibition in LA.

830
00:34:15,679 --> 00:34:17,180
The criticism I received

831
00:34:17,514 --> 00:34:20,183
was that I was too conscious
of the commercial aspect.

832
00:34:20,350 --> 00:34:22,852
To put it more bluntly,

833
00:34:22,936 --> 00:34:26,398
"Why do you care so much
about other people when you're painting?"

834
00:34:26,648 --> 00:34:30,193
They said that my work
is more design than art.

835
00:34:30,277 --> 00:34:31,736
- Kappus.
- Sorry?

836
00:34:32,445 --> 00:34:33,947
- Yes, that's right.
- Right.

837
00:34:34,030 --> 00:34:35,991
- That's what Rilke said to Kappus.
- That's right.

838
00:34:36,616 --> 00:34:39,369
YOU COMPARE YOUR POEMS WITH OTHER POEMS

839
00:34:39,452 --> 00:34:41,621
AND YOU GET UPSET

840
00:34:41,705 --> 00:34:46,918
I BEG YOU TO STOP DOING THAT SORT OF THING

841
00:34:47,002 --> 00:34:51,047
YOU ARE LOOKING OUTSIDE, AND THAT IS
WHAT YOU SHOULD MOST AVOID RIGHT NOW

842
00:34:51,131 --> 00:34:52,799
FROM <i>LETTERS TO A YOUNG POET</i>

843
00:34:52,882 --> 00:34:55,343
And the person who told me this

844
00:34:55,760 --> 00:34:59,222
was the director of the Museum
of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles.

845
00:34:59,306 --> 00:35:02,559
On one wall, there were my sketches.

846
00:35:02,642 --> 00:35:03,935
They saw that

847
00:35:04,019 --> 00:35:06,187
and said, "This is how you should paint.

848
00:35:06,396 --> 00:35:09,899
This is more genuinely you."

849
00:35:09,983 --> 00:35:12,652
That was the critique I got.

850
00:35:12,819 --> 00:35:15,447
At the moment,
I felt offended and embarrassed.

851
00:35:15,530 --> 00:35:19,701
But the next day,
I realized that it was invaluable advice.

852
00:35:19,868 --> 00:35:22,454
After that, I changed my approach.

853
00:35:22,537 --> 00:35:26,750
I decided to do it my way,
without worrying about others.

854
00:35:27,083 --> 00:35:29,919
I already had the New York show
booked for the summer.

855
00:35:30,003 --> 00:35:32,339
The LA show was in March.

856
00:35:32,422 --> 00:35:34,716
When I was preparing for New York,

857
00:35:35,133 --> 00:35:37,177
I didn't send any of my big pieces.

858
00:35:37,260 --> 00:35:39,346
I only sent the small ones

859
00:35:39,429 --> 00:35:42,265
that were mostly pen sketches

860
00:35:42,349 --> 00:35:43,892
to the New York show.

861
00:35:43,975 --> 00:35:46,186
They weren't even colored.

862
00:35:46,269 --> 00:35:49,522
They were just pen drawings.

863
00:35:49,731 --> 00:35:51,733
So the people in New York said,

864
00:35:51,816 --> 00:35:54,986
"Your work usually uses bold colors,

865
00:35:55,070 --> 00:35:56,655
and they're quite big in size.

866
00:35:56,738 --> 00:36:00,200
But all of the ones you sent are small."

867
00:36:00,408 --> 00:36:02,577
They were not very considerate pieces.

868
00:36:02,661 --> 00:36:06,915
They were like X-ray cross sections
of my subconscious,

869
00:36:06,998 --> 00:36:10,794
or my unplanned and unrefined thoughts.

870
00:36:11,044 --> 00:36:14,047
But I was so proud of those pieces.

871
00:36:14,130 --> 00:36:18,343
It was the first time
I was showing my honest, unfiltered self.

872
00:36:18,635 --> 00:36:20,970
Of course, they're not very attractive.

873
00:36:21,054 --> 00:36:24,849
Who would want
those raw, crude drawings on their wall?

874
00:36:24,974 --> 00:36:27,560
That's why I only sold one.

875
00:36:27,644 --> 00:36:29,938
So I paid for it myself

876
00:36:30,021 --> 00:36:32,148
to bring them all back to Korea.

877
00:36:32,232 --> 00:36:35,735
But that exhibition

878
00:36:35,819 --> 00:36:38,488
was a big turning point in my life.

879
00:36:38,571 --> 00:36:41,199
Maybe they were really like,
"Don't even come near."

880
00:36:41,282 --> 00:36:43,785
The owner of the gallery
needs the art to sell.

881
00:36:43,868 --> 00:36:45,954
- It's probably just a rumor.
- I guess.

882
00:36:46,037 --> 00:36:47,956
The gallery needs the art to sell.

883
00:36:48,039 --> 00:36:49,624
They paid for the art

884
00:36:49,708 --> 00:36:52,794
and the insurance to bring it there,

885
00:36:53,002 --> 00:36:55,255
and this punk only sold one piece.

886
00:36:55,338 --> 00:36:58,550
Yes, they might think,
"I don't want you anywhere near here."

887
00:36:58,758 --> 00:37:02,095
But that was
a huge point of realization for me.

888
00:37:02,178 --> 00:37:04,889
All of that happened in 2015.

889
00:37:05,473 --> 00:37:07,767
- You must've felt grateful.
- I did.

890
00:37:07,976 --> 00:37:10,061
They told you because you had the talent.

891
00:37:10,145 --> 00:37:12,063
It probably took courage for them

892
00:37:12,147 --> 00:37:14,107
- Right.
- to tell you that as well.

893
00:37:14,190 --> 00:37:16,359
That kind of advice
is easy to misunderstand

894
00:37:16,443 --> 00:37:18,528
- and feel uncomfortable about.
- That's true.

895
00:37:18,611 --> 00:37:22,157
It's similar to what Rilke said.

896
00:37:22,240 --> 00:37:23,950
Someone important showed up

897
00:37:24,033 --> 00:37:26,327
and gave me the perfect advice.

898
00:37:26,411 --> 00:37:28,413
That's also why I like this book.

899
00:37:28,496 --> 00:37:31,499
When things don't go well,

900
00:37:31,583 --> 00:37:34,043
or I feel like I've hit a wall,

901
00:37:34,127 --> 00:37:36,379
I try to look back on myself.

902
00:37:36,463 --> 00:37:39,048
I ask, "Have I been hypocritical?

903
00:37:39,132 --> 00:37:41,217
Have I been caring too much about others?

904
00:37:41,301 --> 00:37:42,677
What has been bothering me?"

905
00:37:42,761 --> 00:37:44,888
I take a step back and examine that.

906
00:37:45,305 --> 00:37:47,140
That's not an easy thing to do, is it?

907
00:37:47,223 --> 00:37:48,558
- Of course, it's very hard.
- Right.

908
00:37:48,641 --> 00:37:50,643
- Instead of wasting energy
- Yes.

909
00:37:50,727 --> 00:37:53,104
- worrying about the critics,
- Yes.

910
00:37:53,188 --> 00:37:55,523
- you redirect that energy inward.
- Right.

911
00:37:56,024 --> 00:37:58,026
Even though you know you should do this,

912
00:37:58,109 --> 00:37:59,694
- it's easy to forget over time.
- Of course.

913
00:37:59,778 --> 00:38:02,906
That's why I like to read this book
again and again.

914
00:38:02,989 --> 00:38:04,032
- I see.
- Yes.

915
00:38:04,365 --> 00:38:06,659
The New York gallery owner
must've been upset.

916
00:38:06,743 --> 00:38:07,952
They must've wanted to sell.

917
00:38:08,036 --> 00:38:10,955
- The gallery owner there? I suppose.
- Yes.

918
00:38:11,206 --> 00:38:13,124
- They must be watching...
- How are you doing?

919
00:38:13,208 --> 00:38:15,084
Yes, well, give me a call.

920
00:38:15,168 --> 00:38:17,420
I have some pieces
that are a little better.

921
00:38:17,504 --> 00:38:19,214
Let's talk soon.

922
00:38:19,297 --> 00:38:21,508
Have you been keeping in touch?

923
00:38:22,175 --> 00:38:23,384
Well, not really.

924
00:38:25,845 --> 00:38:28,181
But I heard they're doing well.

925
00:38:28,264 --> 00:38:30,225
ANSWERS FOUND IN LONELINESS

926
00:38:30,308 --> 00:38:33,478
- This is my kind of humor.
- I see.

927
00:38:33,561 --> 00:38:35,355
<i>LETTERS TO A YOUNG POET</i>

928
00:38:35,980 --> 00:38:39,734
What's the price you'd set for my book?

929
00:38:39,818 --> 00:38:40,944
How much?

930
00:38:41,361 --> 00:38:43,279
- The price for your book...
- Yes?

931
00:38:45,573 --> 00:38:47,700
- All right! I have it.
- Wait a second.

932
00:38:47,784 --> 00:38:49,494
- Before you set the price,
- Yes?

933
00:38:49,619 --> 00:38:51,412
the appendix was pretty valuable.

934
00:38:53,456 --> 00:38:54,624
- Count that.
- Heaven?

935
00:38:54,707 --> 00:38:55,750
Yes, heaven!

936
00:38:55,834 --> 00:38:57,126
It was a good appendix.

937
00:38:57,210 --> 00:38:58,711
You have to factor that too.

938
00:38:58,795 --> 00:38:59,963
Instead of one book,

939
00:39:00,046 --> 00:39:01,965
I'll give you the price of two books.

940
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:03,341
All right.

941
00:39:04,133 --> 00:39:05,760
I have the price now.

942
00:39:06,219 --> 00:39:09,889
The price of
Ha Jung-woo's favorite book is...

943
00:39:11,391 --> 00:39:13,226
<i>Don Quixote!</i>

944
00:39:13,309 --> 00:39:14,352
What?

945
00:39:15,478 --> 00:39:17,146
That was very unexpected.

946
00:39:17,230 --> 00:39:18,898
"I am who I dream of.

947
00:39:19,190 --> 00:39:21,317
Your value doesn't come
from what you have,

948
00:39:21,401 --> 00:39:22,777
but from what you dream.

949
00:39:22,861 --> 00:39:24,195
Never forget that,

950
00:39:24,320 --> 00:39:27,949
and continue walking
on your path of life."

951
00:39:28,032 --> 00:39:30,118
I, Hocrates, will be rooting for you.

952
00:39:30,201 --> 00:39:31,494
- All right.
- One moment.

953
00:39:32,954 --> 00:39:34,289
I'll pay you for the book.

954
00:39:35,582 --> 00:39:36,833
Let's see.

955
00:39:37,208 --> 00:39:39,335
- You gave me the equivalent of two books.
- Yes.

956
00:39:39,419 --> 00:39:40,879
So, here are two for you.

957
00:39:41,212 --> 00:39:42,922
- Here, take them.
- Thank you.

958
00:39:43,590 --> 00:39:45,925
THE NOBLE MADNESS OF MAN
Don Quixote by Cervantes.

959
00:39:46,009 --> 00:39:47,302
CHARGING TOWARD HIS IDEALS
Have you read it before?

960
00:39:47,385 --> 00:39:48,386
No, I haven't.

961
00:39:48,469 --> 00:39:51,222
I saw the play,
but I haven't read the novel.

962
00:39:51,306 --> 00:39:52,849
Before we finish,

963
00:39:52,932 --> 00:39:54,517
- let's shout it out loud.
- Okay.

964
00:39:54,601 --> 00:39:57,312
Ha Jung-woo's tasty life
told in <i>Hodong's Bookshop.</i>

965
00:39:57,395 --> 00:40:00,690
That was a great read!

966
00:40:00,982 --> 00:40:02,025
Thank you.

967
00:40:02,400 --> 00:40:03,401
The end!

968
00:40:03,484 --> 00:40:09,490
WHO IS HA JUNG-WOO?
A MAN WHO ENDLESSLY WALKS THE PATH OF LIFE

969
00:40:36,434 --> 00:40:38,436
Subtitle translation by Kim Hyun-ji
